  <content>
    <title>Static Application Security Testing (SAST) in CI/CD</title>

    <summary>SAST analyzes source code before execution to identify vulnerabilities early ("shift-left" security). Integrate Semgrep, CodeQL, or SonarQube into every PR pipeline and block on CRITICAL+HIGH findings only; expose MEDIUM/LOW as informational at first, then tighten over time.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>SAST catches vulnerabilities before deployment but may miss runtime issues. It is the fastest feedback loop in the security pipeline — running on the diff at PR time. CodeQL uses semantic analysis (88% accuracy, 5% false positives), Semgrep uses pattern matching (82% accuracy, 12% FP) and is highly extensible with custom rules; Snyk Code applies AI-driven analysis. Early detection reduces remediation cost by orders of magnitude compared to finding the same issue in production.</p>
      <p>Agent workflow: SAST results arrive as SARIF; agents read the SARIF via `gh api`, triage with reachability/exploitability evidence, and open single-purpose fix PRs. Pin scanner versions and rule packs — silent updates create flaky CI.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any project that ships code to production — SAST is the minimum viable security gate.</item>
        <item>Wiring SAST into a PR check so developers get feedback before merge.</item>
        <item>Custom rule authoring for domain-specific patterns (e.g., hardcoded secrets, SQL interpolation).</item>
        <item>Generating SARIF for GitHub Advanced Security / GitLab Code Quality.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Replacing DAST — SAST cannot find runtime vulnerabilities (auth bypass, business logic, SSRF).</item>
        <item>Greenfield exploration with fluid requirements — false-positive volume will drown the team before rules are tuned.</item>
        <item>One-off scripts or scratch repos — overhead exceeds value.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="tool-selection">
      <p>Choose the SAST tool that fits your stack and hosting:</p>
      <list>
        <item>CodeQL — semantic analysis, GitHub-native, best accuracy, runs as GitHub Action. Best for GitHub-centric teams.</item>
        <item>Semgrep — pattern matching, custom rules, fast, CI-agnostic. Best when you need custom rule flexibility or cross-platform CI.</item>
        <item>Snyk Code — AI-driven, strong autofix PRs, SaaS-hosted. Best for open-source-heavy projects.</item>
        <item>SonarQube — code quality + security combined, self-hostable. Best when code quality metrics matter alongside security.</item>
        <item>Bandit (Python), gosec (Go), Brakeman (Rails) — language-native SAST, zero config for single-language repos.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <rules>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Block PR merge on CRITICAL and HIGH SAST findings only; expose MEDIUM and LOW as informational annotations. Tighten thresholds over time as baseline noise decreases.</statement>
        <rationale>Blocking on every finding causes alert fatigue and trains developers to ignore or bypass the gate. Start narrow and expand coverage as the team becomes comfortable with the tool's signal-to-noise ratio.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pin scanner image digests and rule-pack versions in CI; bump them on a defined schedule (e.g., monthly), never silently via floating tags.</statement>
        <rationale>Silent rule-pack updates change what is flagged, causing previously-passing PRs to fail without any code change — making CI untrustworthy.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set a baseline on first integration to ignore pre-existing issues; only gate on new issues introduced in the PR diff.</statement>
        <rationale>Retrofitting SAST into a legacy codebase without a baseline produces thousands of findings in the first run, blocking all new work. Address technical security debt separately with a dedicated sprint.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </rules>

    <example type="good" title="Semgrep CI integration with SARIF upload">
      <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .github/workflows/semgrep.yml
name: Semgrep
on:
  pull_request: {}
  push:
    branches: [main, master]

jobs:
  semgrep:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    container:
      image: semgrep/semgrep
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Run Semgrep
        run: semgrep ci --sarif --output semgrep.sarif
        env:
          SEMGREP_APP_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.SEMGREP_APP_TOKEN }}

      - uses: github/codeql-action/upload-sarif@v3
        if: always()
        with:
          sarif_file: semgrep.sarif
]]></code>
      <note>Using `semgrep ci` respects the project's .semgrepignore and pulls managed rules from the Semgrep AppSec Platform when a token is provided.</note>
    </example>

    <example type="good" title="CodeQL GitHub Actions integration">
      <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .github/workflows/codeql.yml
name: CodeQL
on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
  pull_request:
    branches: [main]
  schedule:
    - cron: '0 6 * * 1'  # Weekly Monday 6AM

jobs:
  analyze:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    permissions:
      security-events: write
      actions: read
      contents: read

    strategy:
      matrix:
        language: [javascript, python]

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Initialize CodeQL
        uses: github/codeql-action/init@v3
        with:
          languages: ${{ matrix.language }}
          queries: +security-extended,security-and-quality

      - name: Autobuild
        uses: github/codeql-action/autobuild@v3

      - name: Perform CodeQL Analysis
        uses: github/codeql-action/analyze@v3
        with:
          category: "/language:${{ matrix.language }}"
]]></code>
    </example>

    <example type="good" title="Custom Semgrep rule for hardcoded secrets">
      <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .semgrep/rules/no-hardcoded-secrets.yaml
rules:
  - id: hardcoded-password
    patterns:
      - pattern-either:
          - pattern: password = "..."
          - pattern: PASSWORD = "..."
          - pattern: passwd = "..."
    message: "Hardcoded password detected"
    languages: [python, javascript, typescript]
    severity: ERROR

  - id: hardcoded-api-key
    pattern-regex: '(?i)(api[_-]?key|apikey)\s*[=:]\s*["\'][a-zA-Z0-9]{20,}["\']'
    message: "Possible hardcoded API key"
    languages: [generic]
    severity: WARNING
]]></code>
    </example>

    <example type="bad" title="Blocking on every severity level">
      <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# Semgrep configured to fail on all severities including INFO/WARNING
- name: Run Semgrep
  run: semgrep ci --error --severity WARNING
]]></code>
      <note>This blocks PRs on low-signal findings, trains the team to add `--no-verify` flags or ignore CI, and makes the security gate useless.</note>
    </example>

    <section name="llm-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="generate-semgrep-rule"><![CDATA[
Create a Semgrep rule that detects [vulnerability type] in [language].

Requirements:
- Pattern should match [specific code pattern]
- Severity: [critical/high/medium/low]
- Include message explaining the vulnerability
- Add fix suggestion if possible
- Include test cases (positive and negative)

Output format: YAML rule with comments
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="analyze-sast-findings"><![CDATA[
Analyze these SAST findings and provide:

1. Risk assessment for each finding
2. False positive likelihood (low/medium/high)
3. Prioritized remediation order
4. Code fix suggestions

Findings:
[paste SAST output]

Consider:
- Exploitability
- Data sensitivity
- Attack surface exposure
- Existing mitigations
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="create-codeql-query"><![CDATA[
Write a CodeQL query for [language] that detects [vulnerability type].

Requirements:
- Query should find [specific pattern]
- Include metadata (name, description, severity)
- Optimize for performance
- Include query help documentation

Example vulnerable code:
[paste example]
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Evaluate tools for your language stack: CodeQL (GitHub repos), Semgrep (custom rules needed), Snyk Code (open-source heavy), SonarQube (code quality + security).</check>
      <check>Configure IDE integration for immediate developer feedback before commit.</check>
      <check>Add SAST to CI pipeline as a PR check with SARIF upload to GitHub Security tab.</check>
      <check>Configure severity thresholds: block on CRITICAL+HIGH, annotate MEDIUM+LOW.</check>
      <check>Set up baseline to ignore existing issues on first integration.</check>
      <check>Document custom rules and exceptions with justification and owner.</check>
      <check>Review and update custom rules quarterly; track false positive rate and tune.</check>
      <check>Keep scanner versions pinned; bump on a schedule.</check>
    </checklist>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Auto-fix bots regress functionality: they upgrade a transitive dep across a major version and break the build silently — require full test pass and human review before merging any auto-fix PR.</p>
      <p>Severity inflation: CVSS scores often overestimate real risk; agents that gate on CVSS alone block trivial PRs. Use reachability evidence (Endor Labs, Snyk Reachability, Semgrep) to reduce false positives 70-90%.</p>
      <p>Prompt injection via dependency README: an attacker-controlled README can change LLM behavior during scan triage; fence inputs when feeding README content to the triage agent.</p>
    </section>

